what it fixes.<br /><br />Yes, the summary line says "Fix unused variable warning", but it<br />doesn't talk about why that variable is unused and why it's not<br />removed entirely.<br /><br />And it's not obvious in the diff either, because the context isn't<br />sufficiently large.<br /><br />So a comment along the lines of "the variable is only used by an<br />'assert()', so when asserts are disabled the compiler sees no use at<br />all" or similar would be appreciated.<br /><br />Of course, the alternative would be to make the backup definition of<br />'assert()' actually evaluate the argument. That's not what the<br />standard assert() is supposed to do, but whatever, and the zstd use<br />doesn't care.<br /><br />So using<br /><br />    #define assert(condition) ((void)(condition))<br /><br />instead would also fix the warning at least in kernel use (but not<br />necessarily outside the kernel - the standard C 'assert.h' is just<br />evil).<br /><br />                  Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
